  "text": "The N-value is based on adjusting both the methylated and unmethylated signals relative to the expected signals, given the observed standard deviations for signals. While these normalized signals have little meaning in themselves, the induced β measures the relative strength of the methylated and unmethylated signals in relation to the expected signals, given the standard deviations. The important measure in this case is the normalized β. Comparing equations (1) and [CITATION_1] shows that the N-value can be viewed as a version of the M-value rescaled by the standard deviation. We will further show that this rescaling results in a normalization of the signals, adjusting the distribution of intensities that vary among samples with different standard deviations. The analysis of differential methylation using all three quantification methods (β, M, and N), is next considered using data from a pilot experiment.",
